The remainder is all masks added together, and inverted. We need to account for this to ensure every pixel has some regional prompt. This can happen when masks are not fully accurate or resampled.
Perturbed Attention Guidance improves the coherency of 'important' items in the scene. It also slows the generations, so this is a tradeoff of speed, vs quality.
Differential diffusion allows inpainting with an 8bit greyscale mask, instead of a bitmask. This allows varied strength of inpainting and denoising.
We create a weighted controlnet mask. This allows us control over how strictly regions should adhere to the normals and HED outlines.

Attention couple changes the way masked regional prompting is handled. Broadly speaking it takes all the prompt regions at once and calculates, ending up with a dramatically faster generation speed. Secondly, it retains cohesive and subtle global effects like reflectance and lighting much better with larger numbers of regions.
